  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. A qubit begins as two complex amplitudes, which sounds like four numbers. Yet every pure qubit state fits at one point on a globe. Where did the extra dimensions go?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "Why can every pure state of a qubit be represented by one point on the surface of the Bloch sphere?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — THE QUBIT",
            "segment": "Four Numbers Become Two Angles",
            "greeting": "Hallo, Liam",
            "runningText": "removing normalization and global phase…",
            "output": [
              "A qubit starts with two complex amplitudes.",
              "Only two physically distinct parameters remain."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.35,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "A classical bit offers two isolated choices: zero or one. A pure qubit includes those poles and a continuous family of coherent superpositions between them.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.07,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "Start with alpha times zero plus beta times one. Alpha and beta are complex. That is four real numbers.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.87,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Normalization says the squared magnitudes add to one. That one constraint removes one real degree of freedom, leaving three.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "subtract"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.74,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Multiplying the entire state by the same phase changes no measurement probability. Global phase is physically redundant, so one more parameter disappears. Two remain.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.3,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Write those two parameters as angles theta and phi. Theta sets latitude from the north pole. Phi sets longitude around the sphere.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.34,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The standard form is cosine theta over two times zero, plus e to the i phi times sine theta over two times one. One normalized ray, specified by two angles.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.84,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "At the north pole theta is zero, so the state is zero. At the south pole theta is pi, so it is one, apart from an irrelevant overall phase.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.92,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "On the equator, zero and one have equal magnitude. Longitude phi changes their relative phase, producing physically different interference behavior.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.19,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "For theta equals pi over two and phi equals pi over two, the Bloch arrow points along plus y. A z measurement is still fifty-fifty; a y measurement is certain plus.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "calculate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.2,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "One crucial qualifier: the surface represents pure qubit states. Statistical mixtures live inside the Bloch ball, with the completely mixed state at its center.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "qualify"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.73,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "So the globe is not decorative. Normalization and global-phase redundancy compress four real coordinates into the two physical angles of a pure qubit.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.32,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:14:40"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Your turn. Put theta at pi over two and phi at zero. Locate the arrow, then predict the probabilities for measuring zero and one.",
